			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3398">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Susan Griffin&rsquo;s main purpose in &ldquo;<a href="/article/3038/">Ideologies of Madness</a>&rdquo; [Issue 157] is apparently to explore how the dualism of self and other results in a civilization capable of nuclear holocaust. On the whole she presents a strongly developed thesis; but her argument is flawed by some historical and cultural inaccuracies.</p>

<p>She holds the &ldquo;church&rdquo; (which one?) responsible for the dualism of matter and spirit: &ldquo;Matter &mdash; or body and earth &mdash; was the corrupt, degraded region, belonging to the Devil. Spirit &mdash; or the realm of pure intellect and heavenly influence &mdash; belonged to God, and was won only at the expense of flesh.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The notion that matter belonged to the Devil was current in the Middle Ages among the Albigensians of southern France. It was condemned as a heresy by the Catholic Church, and revived in a different form by Calvin during the Protestant Reformation. St. Augustine in <em>The City of God</em> argued that matter, although subject to change, reflects the perfection of God in the beauty of its design. He further argued that the universe is a continuum, that all created objects exist in a hierarchy of good, and that evil is simply nonexistence, or the turning away from the source of all good.</p>

<p>We turn away from this source because of the &ldquo;dualism&rdquo; that Susan Griffin identifies as a species of madness &mdash; the division of &ldquo;self&rdquo; and &ldquo;other,&rdquo; which Augustine called &ldquo;pride.&rdquo; Further, God has never been an exclusionary &ldquo;being&rdquo; in orthodox Catholic teaching, but rather the source of all being &mdash; the circle whose circumference is nowhere and whose center is everywhere.</p>

<p>Not to appreciate the details of this profundity in Augustine, and in &ldquo;church&rdquo; thinking generally, is to ignore the real power and vitality of the Christian tradition, and its capacity for renewing itself in times of crisis by returning to the radical &mdash; and nondual &mdash; experience of contemplation.</p>

<p>Our civilization is not entirely mad, just as all pornography is not uniformly violent, demeaning to women, or fearful of sexual experience. Insanity and wisdom emerge together. Griffin recognizes this truth in her description of the two selves, &ldquo;one acknowledged and one hidden,&rdquo; but I wonder if, in seeking to legitimize the notion of a &ldquo;hidden&rdquo; self, she does not fall into the very dualism that she cautions us against.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author"><a href="/contributors/stephen-t-butterfield">Stephen T. Butterfield</a><br>Shrewsbury, Vermont</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

